\begin_layout Abstract
Recording locations of mobile nodes and connectivity between them is essential
 in the study of various types of wireless networks, including but not limited
 to opportunistic networks.
 Working with mobility information gives an extra degree of freedom in the
 study of such networks, while in a contact log, a lot of information like
 the locations of the nodes and their velocities is irretrievably lost.
 On the other hand, contact information can be measured more easily compared
 to detailed locations of the nodes.
 In this paper, we present a solution for inferring mobility from contact
 information.
 This technique uses a simple non-linear optimization approach to suppress
 the problem as a feasibility problem with fundamental constraints on the
 mobility of the nodes.
 In this paper, we introduce our technique and its underlying assumptions,
 and discuss applicability of more than one input to enhance the performance
 of inferred mobility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
mobility trace, contact trace, plausible mobility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\series bold

\backslash
IEEEPARstart
\series default
 command is needed in the first paragraph fo the document.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
IEEEPARstart{
\end_layout

\end_inset

S
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}{
\end_layout

\end_inset

tudies
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of mobile wireless protocols benefit from real-world traces that measure
 and record node locations over time.
 These 
\emph on
mobility traces
\emph default
 can be combined with radio models to produce network connectivity for simulatio
n studies.
 Measuring node locations with fine-grained time and space granularity is
 challenging, however.
 Outdoor positioning systems are sensitive to weather and obstacles, while
 indoor positioning systems generally rely on availability of WiFi or other
 signal infrastructure that may not be available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an alternative, 
\emph on
contact traces
\emph default
 measure and record pairwise node connectivity over time and do not require
 accurate positioning systems.
 Because they come from radio transmissions, contact traces are able to
 capture environmental effects on communication capability, such as obstacle
 effects, that are missing from mobility traces.
 Contact traces can record on-off timing information about links, hence
 they can be more compact than mobility traces that must record data at
 every time instant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contacts are typically recorded by using Bluetooth or WLAN in an infra-structure
less mode.
 All other devices in range are seen as a contact 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aschenbruck2011trace"

\end_inset

.
 Collecting contact traces is challenging, however, as it requires instrumenting
 nodes with collection capability and conducting a well-planned and coordinated
 collection 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

run
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While recording contact opportunities, a lot of information is irretrievably
 lost.
 No information on exact location an velocity of the nodes can be retrieved
 from a contact trace.
 As time elapses, the amount of this information decreases and it becomes
 more and more difficult to even relatively locate the nodes.
 Such traces are only representative of the particular context in which
 they are measured.
 For example, a WiFi radio contact trace seems not to be appropriate to
 study a scenario possessing the same characteristics in every aspect, except
 a Bluetooth radio without running the entire trace collection experiment
 again which carries a significant organizational overhead in preparing,
 distributing and collecting contact loggers, not to mention non-technical
 issues related to legality and participant consent.
 In a similar fashion, every small change in the contact scenario necessitates
 repetition of the whole collection process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contact trace collection and analysis have been reported in the literature
 and have been used extensively to study mobile networks for various settings
 ranging from a campus scenario 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pmtr2008"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nus2006"

\end_inset

 to a conference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "infocom2006"

\end_inset

 to urban scenarios 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "natarajan2007understanding"

\end_inset

 or a disaster area.
 Aschenbruck et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aschenbruck2009modeling"

\end_inset

 has summarized these types of datasets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in the problem of inferring a plausible mobility trace
 from a contact trace.
 By 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plausible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we mean a trace that is consistent with the contacts, and not originating
 from a given radio model.
 In general, there may be multiple mobility traces that are consistent with
 a given trace.
 We do not attempt to enumerate them.
 Although this plausible mobility might not match the original locations,
 it matches to a mobility trace that could have generated the same contact
 trace, or a trace very similar to it.
 It can be discussed that the exact locations of the nodes is not required
 in most the experiments that deal with studying mobility or modifying contacts
 , unless the researcher has access to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mobility trace presenting the same characteristics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coming from the contact domain to the mobility domain, may provide researchers
 with opportunities not present with the contacts alone, such as transforming
 the settings of the original data collection, one that assumes a different
 radio, for example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our proposed algorithm is based on optimizing a mobility trace using the
 limited information from the contacts.
 It operates by solving a feasibility problem for a small set of fundamental
 constraints on mobility of the nodes.
 We will describe the details of the algorithm in this report and we have
 made the code publicly available [CITATION NEEDED]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contributions of this work are summarized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An algorithm to infer mobility information based on contact traces that
 enables richer understanding of mobile networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Application of multiple inputs for the proposed algorithm to enhance re-usabilit
y of the output trace.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this paper is organized as follows [TO BE COMPLETED]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Previous Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of mobility inversion, though, is different from the localization
 problem, in the sense that it combines a contact model, and a contact trace
 showing the opportunities among nodes to get in touch to obtain a mobility
 trace showing their locations using no further information
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These concepts will be more formally defined in the next section
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Few solutions have been proposed for this specific problem.
 Wang et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang2011automatic"

\end_inset

 solves the same problem by dividing it into smaller subproblems, and relying
 on decreasing number of possibilities.
 Our analysis of such approach has proven that the complexity of such solution
 grows exponentially with increasing number of nodes, and hence is only
 applicable to small scenarios.
 Ristanovic et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ristanovic2010tracking"

\end_inset

 suggests a solution that relies on knowledge of some anchor nodes, with
 fixed and known location, which can give a rough estimate of location of
 mobile Bluetooth devices that have a low range.
 The immediate downside is the dependence on the location of devices and
 the underlying technologies used.
 Whitbeck et.
 al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "whitbeck2011encounters"

\end_inset

 has proposed a complete algorithm for the mobility inversion problem inspired
 by the work in dynamic graph drawing.
 They define three fundamental constraints on the mobility of the nodes
 as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||x_{i}(t+\Delta t)-x_{i}(t)||_{2}^{2}\leq v_{max}\Delta t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r-2v_{max}min\{t-p_{ij}^{\uparrow},n_{ij}^{\downarrow}-t\}\leq d_{ij}(t)\leq r
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\leq d_{ij}(t)\leq r+2v_{max}min\{t-p_{ij}^{\downarrow},n_{ik}^{\uparrow}-t\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}(t)$
\end_inset

 are the location of node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and distance between nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at time
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}^{\uparrow}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{ij}^{\uparrow}$
\end_inset

are the previous and the next time that node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will be in contact , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{ij}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

are the previous and the next time that node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will be lose their contact, all relative to the current time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 denotes the transmission range of the nodes 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The paper assumes a simple circular transmission range for the all nodes,
 which is used for the sake of simplicity in many works, but is not the
 best model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first constraint states that no node can move faster than a maximum
 speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{max}$
\end_inset

, and the other two confines the distance between two nodes based on their
 previous and future contact opportunities.
 The authors then define, an attractive force, similar to the classical
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spring
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force on each node from all of its contacts, as well as a repulsive force,
 similar to the classical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Coulomb
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force, as well as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drag
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force to prevent nodes going excessively away from each other when borders
 are not obvious.
 Equilibrium of these forces on each node, determines its location.
 Together, this gives a relative set of locations satisfying the given contacts.
 A major disadvantage of this approach is the necessity of a smart choice
 of many constants involved in the calculation of the forces.
 Since there is no rule of thumb for many of these parameters, the performance
 of the application becomes dependent of the specific scenario under study,
 and it may become a series of trial and errors when such information is
 not available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we define the basic concepts of mobility and contacts as
 they have been used in our proposed algorithm, and provide the background
 knowledge required for understanding the context and technical details
 of our mobility inversion algorithm.
 We start this section by a few definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Contact Trace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contact trace is a log of contact-start and contact-end events, each labeled
 with a time stamp and with the identifiers of the two nodes involved in
 the contact event.
 Mathematically, contact traces can be represented using a sequence of graphs
 showing the connections over time, which are called 
\emph on
evolving graphs
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bui2003evolving"

\end_inset

.
 We are interested in contact traces collected in the course of an experiment.
 In such experiments, mobile devices equipped with a wireless interface
 are attached to moving entities (e.g., people or vehicles).
 These mobile devices sample their environments periodically and log the
 presence of neighboring nodes.
 At the conclusion of the experiment these logs are collected and a contact
 trace is constructed from them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contact-start events occur when two mobile devices come within radio range
 of each other.
 Contact-end events occur when two mobile devices who were previously in
 contact are not within the radio range of each other's devices.
 Many aspects of the radio environment can affect these events.
 In general, contact trace becomes meaningful when studied along with a
 
\emph on
contact model.

\emph default
 In the simplest model, two nodes are defined to be in contact whenever
 their distance is less than a given transmission range, and disconnected
 otherwise.
 There is a debate that this model is too simplistic due to many reasons
 including the existence of obstacles, lack of symmetry in real contacts,
 inequality of signal strength inside the assumed transmission circle, etc
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kotz2003mistaken"

\end_inset

, but this model has been used extensively due its simplicity and the fact
 that it allows to focus on other, perhaps more significant factors in the
 experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\emph on
Mobility Trace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A mobility trace is a log of locations of nodes over time.
 Similar to a contact trace, a mobility trace can also be unsynchronized
 or synchronized, synthetically modeled or corresponding to real data from
 GPS equipped devices or association to the base stations of a 3G/WiFi network.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Mobility Inversion Algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mobility-Inversion-Algorithm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we define the problem and its solution in a mathematical
 framework.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be the number of nodes that reside in a field of size 
\begin_inset Formula $L\times L$
\end_inset

.
 We assume each node has a location in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions, with 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

 in our simulations.
 A contact trace in this setting, corresponds to an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N\times T_{m}$
\end_inset

 matrix of adjacencies of its corresponding evolving graph 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bui2003evolving"

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the length of the trace .
 A mobility trace is is a 
\begin_inset Formula $d\times N\times T_{m}$
\end_inset

 matrix, where its element 
\begin_inset Formula $(:,i,t)$
\end_inset

 is the location of node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in both dimensions.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:params"

\end_inset

 describes the parameters used in the above description.
\end_layout

