\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The front end of our algorithm is similar to the algorithm of Whitbeck et
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "whitbeck2011encounters"

\end_inset

 except that instead of one contact trace, we can take one or more contact
 traces, their corresponding radio ranges, and an upper bound on speed of
 movements as input and infer a mobility trace that can generate these contacts.O
ur algorithm does not use any initial information or assumption about the
 mobility model of the individuals.
 The only assumptions made are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are in contact once their distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $||x_{i}-x_{j}||_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is less than a given radio range, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and are out of contact if this distance is larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nodes move slower than a given maximum speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 , the distance between the location of a node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $||x_{i}^{t}-x_{i}^{t+1}||_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}\times\Delta t$
\end_inset

 where 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is the difference between snapshots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nodes are always confined inside the mobility field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Single Input Mobility Inversion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Single-Input-Mobility"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we describe the algorithm for a single input contact trace,
 and the generalize to an arbitrary number of inputs in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Multiple-Input-Mobility"

\end_inset

.
 This front end is depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

, where we use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $G=(V,E)$
\end_inset

 for the evolving graph corresponding to the input contact, which is a time-seri
es of graphs 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{t}=(V^{t},E^{t})$
\end_inset

 .
 We use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $G\Leftrightarrow C$
\end_inset

 to show that the evolving graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has the corresponding adjacency matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 , which is a contact trace as defined above, this means that the graphs
 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{t}$
\end_inset

 have adjacencies 
\begin_inset Formula $C(:,:,t)$
\end_inset

.
 The algorithm works in an iterative manner to find the locations of the
 nodes at each time step of the contact trace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Input: 
\series default
Contact Trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N\times N\times T_{m}},$
\end_inset

 Transmission range 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, Maximum speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

, number of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}\leftarrow\mathbf{0}_{d\times N\times T_{m}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Find a set of initial locations 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}(:,:,0)\leftarrow X_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
for
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $:=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
do
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series medium
solve
\series default
 the nonlinear optimization problem in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{t}\Longleftrightarrow C(:,:,t)$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}(:,:,t)\leftarrow X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\leftarrow X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
end for
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Output:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:Basic"

\end_inset

Basic mobility inversion algorithm with one input contact trace
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figures/ReportAlgorithmBasic.eps
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

Optimization algorithm takes a contact traces along with its corresponding
 radio range and a value of maximum speed to infer a mobility in an iterative
 manner.
 Inferred locations for each time step are given as an initial point of
 the solver for the next step.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To complete our description of algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Basic"

\end_inset

, we need to clarify how we find the initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and how we solve the nonlinear optimization of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the optimization problem, proposed in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

, which is done in every iteration of algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Basic"

\end_inset

, we use Limited-memory Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno (l-BFGS-B) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhu1997algorithm"

\end_inset

 which solves a nonlinear optimization or feasibility problem with simple
 bounds on variable.
 the l-BFGS-B, which is a variant of the Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shann
 (BFGS), an approximation of Newton's method that seeks the stationary point
 of a function by finding the zero of its derivative.
 l-BFGS-B, needs an initial point to seek this stationary point, which is
 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

given to it in algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the equation for the first iteration, we use the same method as
 above, except that only constraints corresponding to ranges, and residence
 of locations in the simulations will be considered, and the maximum speed
 constraint, which necessitates a reasonable set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

previous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 locations, will be ignored.
 Since l-BFGS-B still needs an initial point to seek the stationary point
 of the function, we construct a distance matrix by finding the number of
 hops among every pair of nodes in 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{0}\Longleftrightarrow C(:,:,0)$
\end_inset

, and multiplying it by the transmission range 
\begin_inset Formula $R,$
\end_inset

i.e.
 we assume two nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 hops far from each other are at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times R$
\end_inset

, and apply the classical MDS on it, to yield a decent initial point which
 can be then passed to the version of the optimization problem that ignores
 the speed constraint to find the first value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

, which is initial location of nodes as well, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}(:,:,0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multiple Input Mobility Inversion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Multiple-Input-Mobility"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we meet the mobility inversion problem, in case that there
 are multiple inputs.
 Assume that we have contact traces
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},C_{2},...,C_{n}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Each contact trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N\times T_{m}$
\end_inset

matrix as describe in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Mobility-Inversion-Algorithm"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 , with their corresponding transmission ranges, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}\leq R_{2}\leq...\ensuremath{\leq R_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 The algorithm presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Basic"

\end_inset

, can be easily generalized to accept multiple inputs.
 The revised version will be describe as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Input: 
\series default
Contact Trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\{C_{1},C_{2},...,C_{n}\}_{N\times N\times T_{m}}$
\end_inset

 Transmission ranges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{R_{1}\leq R_{2}\leq...\leq R_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, Maximum speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

, number of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Preprocess contact traces
\begin_inset Formula $\{C_{1},C_{2},...,C_{n}\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}\leftarrow\mathbf{0}_{d\times N\times T_{m}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Find a set of initial locations 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}(:,:,0)\leftarrow X_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
for
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $:=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
do
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series medium
solve
\series default
 the nonlinear optimization problem in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:algorithm"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\{G_{1}^{t},G_{2}^{t},...,G_{n}^{t}\}\Longleftrightarrow\{C_{1}(:,:,t),C_{2}(:,:,t),...,C_{n}(:,:,t)\}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}(:,:,t)\leftarrow X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\leftarrow X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
end for
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Output:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{final}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:Multi"

\end_inset

Basic mobility inversion algorithm with one input contact trace
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figures/ReportAlgorithmMulti.eps
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:algorithmMulti"

\end_inset

Optimization algorithm takes multiple contact traces along with their correspond
ing radio ranges and a value of maximum speed to infer a mobility in an
 iterative manner.
 Inferred locations for each time step are given as an initial point of
 the solver for the next step.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pre-processing, a first difference from algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Basic"

\end_inset

, is needed to make sure that the contact traces 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},C_{2},...,C_{n}$
\end_inset

 are compatible.
 We first inspect the contact traces starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

and then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

and so on to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 At any points, if two nodes are not connected in a contact trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 with transmission 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 at a certain time, we need to force all contact traces 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

 with transmission ranges 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}\geq R_{i}$
\end_inset

 not to have a connection between the same nodes at the same time
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If those nodes are labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, respectively, then if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}(l,k,t)=0$
\end_inset

, we force 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}(l,k,t)\leftarrow0,$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}\geq R_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A follow-up inspection is then performed, starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n-1}$
\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}.$
\end_inset

 At any points, if two nodes are connected in a contact trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 with transmission 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 at a certain time, we need to force all contact traces 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

 with transmission ranges 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}\leq R_{i}$
\end_inset

 to have a connection between the same nodes at the same time
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If those nodes are labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, respectively, then if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}(l,k,t)=0$
\end_inset

, we force 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}(l,k,t)\leftarrow1,$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}\leq R_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The pre-processing ensures that there is no contradiction in the contact
 traces.
 Note that such contradictions are possible, if we use real traces, and
 skip the pre-processing due to environmental effects, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem to be solved in the iterations of algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Multi"

\end_inset

 is the second revision to the basic algorithm.
 In this case, for every two nodes, we can limit their distance at every
 time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to two values.
 One is the transmission range 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{k}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the contact trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

with the largest transmission range that still shows the two nodes not to
 be connected, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}(i,j,t)=0$
\end_inset

, and the other is the transmission range 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{l}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the contact trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{l}$
\end_inset

with the smallest transmission range that still shows the two nodes to be
 connected, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}(i,j,t)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that in general case, we may have 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{k}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the two nodes are connected in all contact traces for that specific time
 instance, and we can also have 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{l}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that the two nodes are never connected in any contact trace for that specific
 time instance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Except the above mentioned revisions, the optimization problem is solved
 with similar techniques as the ones discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Single-Input-Mobility"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discussions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we briefly review the main advantages of our mobility inversion
 algorithm, compared to the force based algorithm of Whitbeck et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "whitbeck2011encounters"

\end_inset

.
 We will also point out the drawbacks of the algorithm.
 We will discuss the performance metrics in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simplicity of the front-end is the first advantage of our algorithm.
 In case of the force-based algorithm, calling the algorithm needs not only
 the input contact trace, but also many parameters need to be set.
 These include the rigidity constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and the damping factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 in the attractive force, the intensity constant 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 , cutoff distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max},$
\end_inset

and parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

that affect the intensity of the repulsive force with distance, as well
 as the strength parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 of the drag force.
 There is no general rule for setting these parameters, and for the algorithm
 to perform well, these need to be set in a trial and error.
 On the other hand, the optimization algorithm does not need any external
 parameters other than a maximum speed and transmission range, which are
 natural to consider for every scenario and are present in the force-based
 algorithm nevertheless.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A drawback, present in both algorithms is the contact model.
 It has been discussed in the literature, many other factors including but
 not limited to presence of obstacles, fading, path-loss, etc affect the
 connectivity model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kotz2003mistaken"

\end_inset

.
 Despite this, the optimization mobility inversion algorithm is designed
 in a modular manner so that any contact model can be integrated into it.
 Since the solver at the heart of our algorithm, BFGS, can solve any nonlinear
 optimization problem, a new contact model that can be described mathematically,
 and can be derived from a contact trace, possibly with additional information,
 can replace the circular model, without affecting the other modules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second future improvement to the algorithm, should target the computational
 complexity.
 The BFGS solver used in the algorithm does not scale linearly with the
 number of nodes, and this can be a serious drawback to the performance
 of the algorithm on large traces.
 The authors do not know of any solver or feasible modification at the moment
 that can address this completely.
 The only suggestion, which can give marginal improvements, but does not
 remove the nonlinear increases of running time with the number of nodes
 is to implement the algorithm in a lower level language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Performance Evaluation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we evaluate the performance of the mobility inversion algorithm
 proposed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Metrics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Metrics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before presenting the evaluations, we need to define a performance metric
 to measure how 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the performance of the algorithm on a trace.
 To do this, in the very general framework ,we need to derive measures of
 comparison from the inputs and the outputs of the algorithm.
 Such comparison can be done in three levels as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lowest level of evaluation is done with mobility-mobility comparison.
 Assuming that we have access to the mobility trace from which the input
 contact trace originated, which is only viable for test purposes, we can
 compare the original input mobility trace and the output mobility trace
 for each location, and report a mean squared error over time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $E_{location}=\frac{1}{N^{2}\times T_{m}}\sum_{i,j,t}||X_{original}(i,j,t)-X_{inferred}(i,j,t)||^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset

We do not expect a good matching in mobility nevertheless, as the proposed
 feasibility does not have a unique solution, and we have shown that it
 actually has many solutions which makes it almost impossible to pick the
 desired output mobility among all these possible solutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next level, we compare the contact traces.
 While the input to our algorithm is a contact trace, we can infer an output
 contact trace with the proper transmission range that the algorithm has
 used at the output and a proper contact model We can then compare the two
 corresponding evolving graphs over time based on the number of missing
 links, i.e.
 present in the input contact trace and missing in the inferred contact
 trace, extra links, i.e.
 only seen in the inferred contact trace, and the sum of these two numbers.
 While a low number of link errors in this level is very desired to be seen
 and is sufficient to have a successful mobility inference, it is not necessary
 for our purposes.
 These errors can be defined as a function of time as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{missing\; link}(t)=\frac{\sum_{i,j}(C_{R}(i,j,t)\wedge(\neg C'_{R}(i,j,t)))}{\sum_{i,j}(C_{R}(i,j,t)\wedge\mathbf{1})}\times100
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{extra\; link}(t)=\frac{\sum_{i,j}((\neg C_{R}(i,j,t))\wedge(C'_{R}(i,j,t))}{\sum_{i,j}(C_{R}(i,j,t)\wedge\mathbf{1})}\times100
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{total\; link}(t)=\frac{\sum_{i,j}(C_{R}(i,j,t)\oplus C'_{R}(i,j,t))}{\sum_{i,j}(C_{R}(i,j,t)\wedge\mathbf{1})}\times100
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C'_{R}$
\end_inset

 are contact traces corresponding evolving graph of ground truth, aka the
 input to the algorithm, and derived contact which comes from the inferred
 mobility, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of all ones of the size 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N\times T_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $\neg$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\oplus$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 represent element-wise logical NOT, XOR and AND respectively.
 Note that for such comparison to be reasonable, we need both contact traces
 to correspond to the same transmission range 
\begin_inset Formula $R.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the third level of comparisons, we use the definitions from Chen et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chen2011framework"

\end_inset

 and Bui et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bui2003evolving"

\end_inset

 to compare journeys, i.e.
 space-time paths between node pairs over time.
 In its simplest form, we can categorize node pairs at each time instant
 to three groups:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-pairs: Two nodes that are always reachable in space at every instant of
 time after the current time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ST-pairs: Two nodes that are reachable within a journey of limited duration
 after the current time.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As discussed by Chen et.
 al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chen2011framework"

\end_inset

, A journey, is a space-time path in an evolving graph that connects two
 nodes over the course of time.
 It's represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $J=(R,R_{\delta})$
\end_inset

 in an evolving graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=e_{1},e_{2},...,e_{k}$
\end_inset

, the sequence of edges it traverses, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\delta}=\delta_{1},\delta_{2},...,\delta_{k}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding time instants of edge traversal.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 must be such that each edge traversed is in the evolving graph at the time
 of traversal.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
N-pairs: two that are not reachable after the current time.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that S-pair,ST-pair, and N-pairs are a function of time, e.g., that two
 nodes can be an ST-pair at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

, but an N-pair at another time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can then compare the percentage of S-,SP-, and N-pairs at every instant
 of time for the input and inferred contact trace.
 This shows the connectivity characteristics of the trace, and can be used
 as a metric to compare the two traces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our experiments, we use three mobility models: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Random Waypoint (RWP)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "camp2002survey"

\end_inset

, which is often used for simulation purposes in mobility literature despite
 its known limitations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "conf/infocom/YoonLN03"

\end_inset

.
 In this model speed, direction, and destination of each mobile node is
 chosen randomly and independently of other nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reference Point Group Mobility (RPGM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "roy2011reference"

\end_inset

 which organizes mobile hosts into groups according to their logical relationshi
ps with each group having a logical center known as reference center whose
 movement is followed by all nodes in the group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Disaster Area Model (DA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aschenbruck2009modeling"

\end_inset

 which is based on an analysis of tactical issues of civil protection and
 has added features like heterogeneous area-based movement, obstacles, and
 joining/leaving of nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiments setting consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $50$
\end_inset

 nodes and a duration of 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 time steps.
 RWP and RPGM span over a 
\begin_inset Formula $1000\times1000\: m^{2}$
\end_inset

 field, with a maximum speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $10m/s$
\end_inset

, while DA spans over a 
\begin_inset Formula $350\times350\: m^{2}$
\end_inset

 field, with a maximum speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $20m/s$
\end_inset

,.
 
\end_layout

